To solve this problem, we need to determine the number of subarrays of a given permutation that are Decinc arrays. A Decinc array is one where you can remove a decreasing subsequence to leave an increasing subsequence. 

### Approach
The approach involves using dynamic programming to track two key values for each subarray starting from index `i` to `j`:
1. `f[j]`: The minimal possible last element of the increasing subsequence.
2. `g[j]`: The maximal possible last element of the decreasing subsequence.

For each element `a[j]` added to the subarray starting at `i`, we check if it can be added to the increasing or decreasing subsequence and update `f[j]` and `g[j]` accordingly. The goal is to maintain the minimal `f[j]` and maximal `g[j]` to allow maximum flexibility for future elements.

### Solution Code
```cpp
            if (a[j] > f[j-1]) {
                f[j] = a[j];
                g[j] = g[j-1];
            }
            if (a[j] < g[j-1]) {
                if (f[j] > f[j-1])
                    f[j] = f[j-1];
                if (g[j] < a[j])
                    g[j] = a[j];
            }
```

### Explanation
1. **Initialization**: For each starting index `i`, initialize `f[i]` to a large value (Inf) and `g[i]` to 0.
2. **Dynamic Programming Transition**:
   - For each element `a[j]` in the subarray starting at `i`, check if it can be added to the increasing subsequence. If so, update `f[j]` to `a[j]` and keep `g[j]` as the previous value.
   - Check if `a[j]` can be added to the decreasing subsequence. If so, update `g[j]` to `a[j]` and keep `f[j]` as the previous value if it is smaller.
3. **Update Conditions**: Ensure `f[j]` is the minimum possible and `g[j]` is the maximum possible to allow future elements to be added to either subsequence.

This approach efficiently tracks the necessary states to determine valid Decinc subarrays, ensuring the solution runs in optimal time for large inputs.
